    },
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "When mode is 'reduced' or 'complete', the result will be a namedtuple with\nthe attributes "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "Q"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " and "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "R"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "This is an interface to the LAPACK routines "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "dgeqrf"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "zgeqrf"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ",\n"
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "dorgqr"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ", and "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "zungqr"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "For more information on the qr factorization, see for example:\n"
            },
            {
              "external_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/QR_factorization",
              "href": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/QR_factorization",
              "kind": "link",
              "text": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/QR_factorization"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "Subclasses of "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "ndarray"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " are preserved except for the 'raw' mode. So if\n"
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "a"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " is of type "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "matrix"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ", all the return values will be matrices too."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "New 'reduced', 'complete', and 'raw' options for mode were added in\nNumPy 1.8.0 and the old option 'full' was made an alias of 'reduced'.  In\naddition the options 'full' and 'economic' were deprecated.  Because\n'full' was the previous default and 'reduced' is the new default,\nbackward compatibility can be maintained by letting "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "mode"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " default.\nThe 'raw' option was added so that LAPACK routines that can multiply\narrays by q using the Householder reflectors can be used. Note that in\nthis case the returned arrays are of type fnp.double or fnp.cdouble and\nthe h array is transposed to be FORTRAN compatible.  No routines using\nthe 'raw' return are currently exposed by numpy, but some are available\nin lapack_lite and just await the necessary work."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Notes"
    },
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "lines": [
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "import flopscope as fnp"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "rng = fnp.random.default_rng()"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "a = rng.normal(size=(9, 6))"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "Q, R = fnp.linalg.qr(a)"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "fnp.allclose(a, fnp.dot(Q, R))  # a does equal QR"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "True"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "R2 = fnp.linalg.qr(a, mode='r')"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "fnp.allclose(R, R2)  # mode='r' returns the same R as mode='full'"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "True"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "a = fnp.random.normal(size=(3, 2, 2)) # Stack of 2 x 2 matrices as input"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "Q, R = fnp.linalg.qr(a)"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "Q.shape"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "(3, 2, 2)"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "R.shape"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "(3, 2, 2)"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "fnp.allclose(a, fnp.matmul(Q, R))"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "True"
            }
          ],
          "type": "doctest_block"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "Example illustrating a common use of "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "qr"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ": solving of least squares\nproblems"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "What are the least-squares-best "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "m"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " and "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "y0"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " in "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "y = y0 + mx"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " for\nthe following data: {(0,1), (1,0), (1,2), (2,1)}. (Graph the points\nand you'll see that it should be y0 = 0, m = 1.)  The answer is provided\nby solving the over-determined matrix equation "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "Ax = b"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ", where:"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "language": null,
          "text": "A = array([[0, 1], [1, 1], [1, 1], [2, 1]])\nx = array([[y0], [m]])\nb = array([[1], [0], [2], [1]])",
          "type": "literal_block"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "If A = QR such that Q is orthonormal (which is always possible via\nGram-Schmidt), then "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "x = inv(R) * (Q.T) * b"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ".  (In numpy practice,\nhowever, we simply use "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "lstsq"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ".)"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "lines": [
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "A = fnp.array([[0, 1], [1, 1], [1, 1], [2, 1]])"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "A"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "array([[0, 1],"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "       [1, 1],"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "       [1, 1],"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "       [2, 1]])"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "b = fnp.array([1, 2, 2, 3])"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "Q, R = fnp.linalg.qr(A)"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "p = fnp.dot(Q.T, b)"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "fnp.dot(fnp.linalg.inv(R), p)"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "array([  1.,   1.])"
            }
          ],
          "type": "doctest_block"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Examples"
    }
  ],
